systemic therapies for acute gouty arthritis a cost effectiveness analysis chp pcor freeman spogli institute for international studies center for health policy center for primary care and outcomes research stanford university fsi centers & programs research centers center on democracy development and the rule of law center for international security and cooperation center on food security and the environment stanford health policy the europe center walter h shorenstein asia pacific research center research programs program on energy and sustainable development rural education action program educational programs stanford program on international and cross cultural education inter university center for japanese language studies ford dorsey program in international policy studies affiliated programs center for innovation in global health research programs & projects by topic by expert by geographic area publications featured publications by author by topic by geographic area people directory chp pcor experts guide events upcoming recent with papers podcasts & video news recent opinion around the web about us chp pcor history annual report map & directions contact us about fsi support fsi quick links department of medicine school of medicine fellowships and funding opportunities cdeha request for seed project proposals cadma request for proposals scholarly concentration in health services & policy research rosenkranz prize for health care research in developing countries follow us on twitter events send by email share online share on facebook share on twitter share on google systemic therapies for acute gouty arthritis a cost effectiveness analysis research in progress seminar date and time january 18 2012 1 30 pm 3 00 pm availability open to the public no rsvp required speaker kim reiter md please note all research in progress seminars are off the record any information about methodology and or results are embargoed until publication background gout is a chronic disorder of uric acid metabolism that results in painful attacks of acute inflammatory arthritis current guidelines recommend agents that are effective but are associated with a number of potential toxicities guidelines do not include systemic corticosteroids in spite of clinical trials showing their efficacy in acute gout and good safety profile in the short term more recently the use of biologic agents that inhibit the activity of interleukin 1 il 1 has been explored in patients with acute gout with positive results objective we sought to determine the cost effectiveness of various therapies for acute gout using a decision tree design we modeled the first three days of an acute gout attack incorporating quality of life aspects of the acute gout flare and costs and health effects of adverse drug related events model inputs were obtained from the literature effectiveness was measured in quality adjusted life days and average wholesale drug costs were used for the base case all costs were in 2011 us dollars results our study suggests that systemic corticosteroids are the most cost effective strategy the model was sensitive to the cost of colchicine which became the most cost effective option at a price of approximately $12.00 per 5 day course while a scenario analysis of the biologic drug showed it to be the most effective option its incremental effectiveness over colchicine was small at 0.26 quality adjusted life days and at an incremental cost of over $19000 conclusions systemic corticosteroids appear to be a safe effective and cost effective option for the treatment of acute gouty arthritis and should be incorporated into updated rheumatology society guidelines at its pre patent price colchicine is highly cost effective and may become the most cost effective agent as it comes off patent in 2012 while a long acting biologic appears very effective in terminating acute flares this study suggests that costs of both the drug and of primarily infectious side effects may excee